cmps_spec_rm_wn <- left_join(cmps_spec_rm, gid_names, by="gene_id") %>% 
  select(-mean) %>% 
  relocate(gene_name)

gene sets

minimal description of collections and where to get them:
https://www.gsea-msigdb.org/gsea/msigdb/collections.jsp

a bit more detail info on collections:
https://www.gsea-msigdb.org/gsea/msigdb/collection_details.jsp

hallmark

hallmark <- gmtPathways("h.all.v7.4.symbols.gmt")

this is the Hallmark set, which is kind of a meta set derived from multiple other sets in the MSigDB that reduces redundancy
https://www.cell.com/cell-systems/fulltext/S2405-4712(15)00218-5

cannonical

c2_cannonical <- gmtPathways("c2.cp.v7.4.symbols.gmt")

this is the canonical pathways subset of the c2 collection:
https://www.gsea-msigdb.org/gsea/msigdb/genesets.jsp?collection=CP

it includes the BIOCARTA, WIKIPATHWAYS, REACTOME, KEGG, and PID are three different collections
BIOCARTA: https://maayanlab.cloud/Harmonizome/dataset/Biocarta+Pathways (seems old)
WIKIPATHWAYS: https://www.wikipathways.org/index.php/WikiPathways REACTOME: https://reactome.org/ KEGG: Kyoto Encyclopedia of Genes and Genomes: https://www.genome.jp/kegg/
PID: Pathway Interaction Database: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18832364/ (seems old)

ontology

c5_ontology <- gmtPathways("c5.all.v7.4.symbols.gmt")

entire c5 collection described as ontology gene sets https://www.gsea-msigdb.org/gsea/msigdb/genesets.jsp?collection=C5
GO (gene ontology) gene sets: http://amigo.geneontology.org/amigo
GO:BP (GO biological process, 7481 gene sets)
GO:CC (GO cellular component, 996 gene sets)
GO:MF (GO molecular function, 1708 gene sets)
and
HPO (Human Phenotye Ontology, 4813 gene sets): https://hpo.jax.org/app/

CoMMpass spectra associated with survival outcomes

the following spectra are significant in the CoxPH model
OS: Sp2 + Sp3 + Sp4 + Sp5 + Sp9 + Sp12 + Sp13 + Sp19 + Sp26
PFS: Sp1 + Sp2 + Sp4 + Sp5 + Sp9 + Sp11 + Sp24 + Sp26 + Sp32
TTF: Sp1 + Sp2 + Sp4 + Sp5 + Sp9 + Sp10 + Sp18 + Sp24 + Sp31 + Sp32

fgsea needs preranked vector with names where names are gene names

notes Sp5

UPR/ER/Golgi/protein secretion on the positive end, Chromatin/DNA/cell cycle on the negative end

negative enrichment scores: HALLMARK_E2F_TARGETS and HALLMARK_G2M_CHECKPOINT (related to cell cycle)
positive enrichment score: HALLMARK_UNFOLDED_PROTEIN_RESPONSE (cellular stress response related to the endoplasmic reticulum)

interesting article: https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s12185-016-2016-0
Abstract: “Bortezomib (BTZ), a proteasome inhibitor, was initially reported as an inhibitor of the NF-κB pathway, which plays a critical role in the pathogenesis of multiple myeloma (MM). The NF-κB activity of MM cells is mediated via two distinct pathways, canonical and non-canonical, which show opposing activity after BTZ treatment in MM cells. Recent studies of proteasome inhibition in MM cells reveal that the accumulation of unfolded proteins in the endoplasmic reticulum (ER), referred to as ER stress, triggered the activity of several pro-apoptotic factors and sources of cell stress, such as the accumulation of reactive oxygen species (ROS), which is considered to be the main mechanism of action of BTZ-induced apoptosis. Several factors associated with ER stress and unfolded protein response (UPR) have been identified with the sensitivity of BTZ treatment. Low levels of XBP1, ATF3, and ATF4, which regulate UPR and ER stress-induced apoptosis, have been observed in poor responders to BTZ treatment, and three other genes, KLF9, Nampt, and CDK5, are associated with response to BTZ-containing therapy. These findings contribute to a better understanding of the mechanisms underlying BTZ-induced apoptosis in MM cells; however, further study is needed to develop potential predictive biomarkers of efficacy of BTZ-containing therapy.”

this study: https://www.nature.com/articles/s41408-018-0062-y
implicates the DERL3 gene in MM, DERL3 is the top gene in the several sets relating to ER used for the leading edge analysis above.
also interesting: https://journals.plos.org/plosgenetics/article?id=10.1371/journal.pgen.1003225

review article on UPR and MM: https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2Fs00018-021-03756-3

ATF6 gene is also in the combined list and is important in UPR. Review above says “ATF6 has also been proposed as a predictor of bortezomib sensitivity in MM cells since drug resistance evolves to reduce cellular dependence on the UPR by downregulation of ATF6 and XBP1 expression” and referenes: https://www.nature.com/articles/bcj201640

quick look at CoMMpass data there many people treated with bortezomib, often in combination with others…
